Overview
In data engineering workflows, we often encounter "Sharded Sheets"—datasets where each month or brand is separated into its own tab. Manually merging 100+ sheets is inefficient and prone to errors.

This guide demonstrates how to use the Power of 3D-Referencing combined with the VSTACK and FILTER functions to consolidate hundreds of sheets into a single "Master Data" view using just one formula.

The Problem
Imagine you have a workbook with 120+ sheets named by Brand_Year_Month.

B1_Lumina_2024_01

B1_Lumina_2024_02

...

B1_Solaris_2024_12

Traditional VSTACK requires listing every single sheet name, which is hit by the character limit and is a nightmare to maintain.

The Solution: 3D-Range Formula
Instead of listing every sheet, we use the "Start:End" syntax. This tells Excel to grab every sheet sitting between two specific tabs.

📝 The Master Formula
Excel
=LET(
    rawData, VSTACK('B1_Lumina_2024_01:B1_Zenith_2024_12'!A2:I500),
    FILTER(rawData, CHOOSECOLS(rawData, 1) <> "")
)
Breakdown of the Logic:
'StartSheet:EndSheet'!Range: This is the "3D" part. It treats the tabs like a deck of cards. As long as your sheets are physically ordered between Lumina_01 and Zenith_12, Excel will suck them all into the stack.

VSTACK(...): Vertically appends the arrays from every sheet.

LET(rawData, ...): We define a variable to keep the formula clean and performant.

FILTER(..., CHOOSECOLS(..., 1) <> ""): Since we selected up to row 500 for each sheet, many rows might be empty. This step removes null rows based on the first column (Primary Key/ID) so your master list is clean.

⚠️ Pro-Tips for Data Integrity:
Sheet Order Matters: The 3D-reference depends on the physical position of the tabs. Ensure your "Start" and "End" sheets wrap around the data you want to include.

Schema Consistency: All sheets must follow the same schema (Columns A to I). If one sheet has an extra column, the stack will misalign.

Single Quotes: Always wrap sheet names in single quotes ('SheetName') if the names contain spaces or special characters (like parentheses).

Implementation Example (Anonymized Brands)
If your workbook contains these brands:

Lumina (Premium Skincare)

Apex Gear (Apparel)

Nova Tech (Electronics)

Zenith (Footwear)

Your consolidated formula would look like this:

Excel
=FILTER(
    VSTACK('B1_Lumina_2024_01:B1_Zenith_2024_12'!A2:I500), 
    INDEX(VSTACK('B1_Lumina_2024_01:B1_Zenith_2024_12'!A2:A500), , 1) <> ""
)
Why use this over VBA?
No Macro Security Issues: Works in standard .xlsx files.

Real-time: The data updates instantly if you change a value in any sub-sheet.

Low Maintenance: Adding a new month? Just drag the new sheet into the middle of the "wrapped" range, and the formula captures it automatically.

